Rating: 3
Took me a while to get this to work for me. Loved the falvor, but don't have an outdoor grill and needed for it to work indoors in a gas oven. Wanted a recipe that served two or four, not 6 or 12. Also needed for brine to work more quickly since I often don't know the night before what I'm going to make for dinner that night. Here's what worked (and didn't) for me. First, the brine. Three cups water, 1/2 cup Kosher salt (or 1/4 cup table salt), 1/2 cup sugar, and the rest of the brine ingredients as they are for 12. Marinate anywhere from 1 to 8 hours. Yes, even 1 hour can make a difference. Cooking: Didn't like the original baking option. I want carmelized edges on my pork chops. Baking didn't give it to me. Neither did an attempt at sauteeing. Finally got what I wanted when I broiled them. Rub ingredients were 1 tablespoon brown sugar per chop, 1/3 generous teaspoon cumin per chop, and (I like spicy, real spicy!) a bit less than 1/8 teaspoon cayenne per chop. Preheat broiler, set rack on the lowest level, spread top of chops with 1/2 the rub, broil 6 minutes, turn and spread chops with remaining rub, and broil six minutes more. Now that I've got it the way I want it, it will be on regular rotation for me. Terrific flavor from the get go, just needed to tweak it to satisfy my preferences.

